	id="Illu_Sequence">
	<title>Sequence: Illustration</title>
	<sub.page.body>
		<block>
			<para>A sequence <latex>(a_n)</latex> of real numbers associates to each <latex>n\in \NNr</latex> a number in <latex>\RNr</latex>. The graphic below illustrates this process for the first 9 sequence elements.</para>
			<figure>
				<img src="ims/Sequence.png"></img><!-- svg available -->
			</figure>
			<para>Here we have approximately</para>
			<ol>
				<li><para><latex>a_0 \approx 3.6</latex></para></li>
				<li><para><latex>a_1 \approx 0.5</latex></para></li>
				<li><para><latex>a_2 \approx -0.3</latex></para></li>
				<li><para><latex>a_3 \approx 3.8</latex></para></li>
				<li><para><latex>a_4 = -2</latex></para></li>
				<li><para><latex>a_5 \approx -4.8</latex></para></li>
				<li><para><latex>a_6 \approx -2.4</latex></para></li>
				<li><para><latex>a_7 \approx 0.3</latex></para></li>
				<li><para><latex>a_8 \approx 4.5</latex></para></li>
				<li><para><latex>a_9 \approx 4.4</latex></para></li>
			</ol>
		</block>
		<block>
			<para>Note that a sequence might, but need not, display any regularity.</para>
		</block>
	</sub.page.body>
</sub.page>